¹2. incesto stupro: Cicero represents the act of Clodius as a duplex crimen, incesto referring to the Bona Dea, and stupro to Pompeia. Cf. Dig. 48. 18. 5. He continually calls the offence of Clodius stuprum, e. g. Har. Resp. 33, 38, 44. The conjecture os Rau, who, from the Schol. Bob, would read incessu, and cut out stupro as a gloss, is attractive‚ since incestu would exactly balance interitu. Resp. 4 ex incesto stupro . . emissum, GE. give incestu and stupro is sup. lin. in G, while Dom. 105 incesto flagitio et stupro, G. omits et stupro. So, de Aere al. iii. 2 nihil de incestis stu- prisquestuses‚theMS.givesincestusstupris. However, the text of the Scholiast is too corrupt to base a conjecture upon, and the confusion of these words is constant.

3. iudicium decern.: for the facts see Att. i. 16. The senate had wished the jurors to be selected by the praetor, but under the lex Fufia, which was actually carried, they were chosen by sortitio in the usual manner.

9. non . . . necessaria: I mark this as a parenthesis to bring out the connection of thought. Non . . . neces- saria is a side remark, while nisi vero takes up non contra remp. For the topic cf. de Or. iii. 11 Sulpicio . . . ferro erepta vita est, et poena temeritatis non sine magno reip. malo constituta.

ulla. . . . umquam: the repetition is the usual one for the sake of emphasis: cf. nulla . . . ubzquam supr. aliquando aliquid § 67, &c. For the variant illa cf. Madvig [Ep. Cr. p. 68] on Verr. iv. 53, quod umquam . . . ulla [v- l. illa j in provincia suit? It would here mean the ‘course of defence ‘previously spoken of,' a sense ftequently found of a plea urged in a law-court, e. g. ad Herenn. ii. 15 item illa defensio tenuis est. This does not seem appropriate here.

10. dies: used for the events os a day, especially of revolution, or calamity. Cf. Att. x. 8. 7 non fuisset illa nox tam acerba Africano . . . non tam dirus ille dies Sullanus . . . C. Mario: Sest. 77 illo Cinnano atque Octaviano die.

quo: see crit. n.

11. aut arma. sata arma, though properly used of the assailant, also in- cludes the resistance made by the State to his attack. Cicero modifies the thought in order to soften the metaphoe, since vulnerarunt, which follows naturally after arma, would be used harshly, if dies were the only subject.
